{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17655110","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17655110"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:59:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:59:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18649"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18649"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.13,0.02,0.02,0.8]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114979"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11381"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18649"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"96985"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26394"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26670"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26938"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"114979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/114979"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe vertebrobasilar circulation delivers blood to posterior regions of the brain including specific areas of the cerebrum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following cerebral regions receives its primary arterial supply from the posterior cerebral artery?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Basal ganglia","Cerebellum","Entire temporal lobe","Frontal and parietal lobes","Occipital and inferior temporal lobes"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eoccipital and inferior temporal lobes\u003C/strong\u003E constitute the primary cerebral territory supplied by the posterior cerebral artery. This vessel arises as one of two terminal branches from the basilar artery and participates in forming the Circle of Willis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontal and parietal lobes\u003C/strong\u003E derive their vascular supply from the anterior and middle cerebral arteries respectively. The middle cerebral artery perfuses the lateral and superior aspects of the temporal lobe, but not the \u003Cstrong\u003Eentire temporal lobe\u003C/strong\u003E. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ebasal ganglia\u003C/strong\u003E are predominantly supplied by perforating branches from the middle cerebral artery, including the lenticulostriate vessels. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebellum\u003C/strong\u003E receives blood from three paired cerebellar arteries: superior, anterior inferior, and posterior inferior.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe posterior cerebral artery plays a crucial role in visual function by supplying the primary visual cortex within the occipital lobe. Additionally, it maintains collateral circulation through the posterior communicating artery, which links it to the anterior circulation via the internal carotid system.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The posterior cerebral artery supplies the occipital lobe and inferior temporal lobe of the cerebrum.","The posterior cerebral artery is a terminal branch of the basilar artery.","The posterior cerebral artery forms part of the Circle of Willis and receives anastomotic supply from the posterior communicating artery."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRe